vine 1.2.0
prefix: ssm
title: Scout source management
---
[ssm] Generalize scout source onboarding and indexing (planning)
Two scout commands replace the current per-vendor pattern (a bespoke
fetch_modal_docs.py-shaped script per source, a hand-added tuple in
search.py's DOCS_SOURCES, a manual search.py --update run): an idempotent
add-source command that registers a new remote source with a TTL, fetches
it, and indexes it; and a separate refresh-stale command that re-fetches
and re-indexes every already-registered source whose TTL has expired,
replacing today's read-the-warning-then-copy-the-refresh-command manual
loop. Both commands need representation on the CLI and as an MCP tool.
Vine graphs are workspace-authored planning artifacts scout never indexes
today; add them as a first-class chunked corpus alongside spec/notes/
proposals/docs, using structural (per-task) chunking rather than raw word
windows, since a task is already the natural retrievable unit.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/command-surface
-> ssm/design/source-registry
-> ssm/design/vine-chunking
-> ssm/design/vine-corpus
-> ssm/implement/add-source
-> ssm/implement/refresh-stale
-> ssm/implement/vine-indexing
---
[ssm/design/source-registry] Design a generic source descriptor (notstarted)
Replace the ad hoc DOCS_SOURCES tuple (vendor name, mirror dir) and the
one-off per-vendor fetch script (fetch_modal_docs.py's llms.txt-walk-and-
mirror logic) with a single descriptor shape covering every source kind
scout will fetch: name, origin URL, ttl_days, fetch strategy (e.g.
llms-txt-mirror, arxiv/openreview pdf, future kinds), and the artifact path
under resources/. The descriptor is the registry entry; sources.json (via
freshness.py) remains the fetched-state ledger, not the registry itself.
No new source-specific script should need to be hand-written after this
lands -- adding a source is filling in a descriptor, not authoring code.
---
[ssm/design/vine-chunking] Design per-task chunking for vine files (notstarted)
Given the chunk-type-adapter interface from ssm/design/chunk-adapters, design vine's adapter: parse a .vine file into its task blocks (reusing bacchus's vine parser semantics: id, name, status, description, decisions) and emit one chunk per task, self-citing as "<vine-stem>#<task-id>#vine" (or similar), including ref blocks. A task whose description exceeds comfortable embedding length may still need internal windowing -- decide whether that stays out of scope for the first cut or is handled by sub-chunking within a task while preserving the task-id citation.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
---
[ssm/design/vine-corpus] Decide where vine chunks attach in search.py (notstarted)
Given per-task chunking from ssm/design/vine-chunking, decide which corpus
absorbs vine chunks. Vines are workspace-authored planning text (like spec/
notes/proposals), not third-party material and not vendor docs, so the
workspace corpus is the default candidate -- confirm no separation concern
(a vine task chunk competing against spec/proposal prose in the same
ranked results) forces a fourth corpus instead. Wire the chosen glob
(root localmodal.vine, proposals/**/*.vine, any future vine locations)
into workspace_chunks() alongside the existing spec/notes/proposals/doc
sources, using the chunker from ssm/design/vine-chunking rather than the
existing word-window helper.
-> ssm/design/vine-chunking
---
[ssm/implement/vine-indexing] Implement vine parsing and corpus wiring (notstarted)
Implement the chunk-type-adapter mechanism designed in ssm/design/chunk-adapters, using it to host the vine adapter designed in ssm/design/vine-chunking, wired into workspace_chunks() per the attachment point decided in ssm/design/vine-corpus. Confirm self-citing ids resolve back to a real task via vine_read, the same way a paper/doc citation resolves back to its source page.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/vine-corpus
---
[ssm/design/command-surface] Design the scout command surface (notstarted)
Before any implementation starts, carefully design and encapsulate the two invocation surfaces: (1) idempotently add a new source -- descriptor in, fetch+index it, no-op if already registered and unexpired; (2) refresh all sources past their TTL -- no argument, scans and re-fetches only stale/missing entries. Each command needs its own representation on both the CLI and the MCP tool surface: exact argument shape, output/error contract, and how both stay isolated from the fetch-strategy internals in ssm/design/source-registry so a new fetch strategy never changes either calling contract.
Accept: the owner confirms the settled two-command CLI + MCP contract before ssm/implement/add-source and ssm/implement/refresh-stale begin.
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/design/chunk-adapters] Design chunk-type adapters for scout (notstarted)
Scout's three corpora (papers/docs/workspace) each chunk every source the same fixed way today: a word-window with overlap, no override. There is no mechanism for a source to declare its own shape and get chunked accordingly. Treat this as a typing problem: design a general chunk-type-adapter interface -- how a source declares a type/kind, how a corpus dispatches to the matching adapter instead of the default word-window chunker, and what an adapter must produce (chunk id, chunk text) to stay compatible with the existing self-citing-id and indexing pipeline (content-hash _sig, manifest.json, versioned index publish).
Minimize assumptions about the first consumer: the vine per-task chunker (ssm/design/vine-chunking) is one adapter instance under this interface, not a special case hardcoded into workspace_chunks(). A future PDF-structure, code-AST, or other structured-source adapter should register the same way.
Accept: the owner confirms one adapter interface shape before ssm/design/vine-chunking is finalized against it.
---
[ssm/implement/add-source] Implement the add-source command (notstarted)
Build the idempotent add command from ssm/design/source-registry and ssm/design/command-surface: given a new source descriptor (name, origin URL, ttl_days, fetch strategy), register it, fetch it, stamp it via freshness.stamp, then run search.py's update path so the result is searchable immediately. Idempotent: re-running with the same descriptor for an already-registered, still-fresh source is a no-op (or an explicit no-op report), not a re-fetch -- re-fetching an unexpired source is the refresh command's job, not this one's. Exposed on both surfaces settled in ssm/design/command-surface: a CLI subcommand and an MCP tool. This supersedes fetch_modal_docs.py and any future per-vendor script as the onboarding path -- once this lands, no ancestor task or doc should still instruct a user to write a new vendor-specific fetch script; existing vendor scripts may be kept working underneath as fetch-strategy implementations, but are no longer the public entry point for adding a source.
-> ssm/design/command-surface
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/implement/refresh-stale] Implement the refresh-stale command (notstarted)
Build the refresh command: no source argument, scan sources.json for TTL-expired or artifact-absent entries via freshness.warnings_for, re-fetch each, re-stamp via freshness.stamp, then run search.py's update path. Only touches sources already past their TTL (or missing their artifact) -- never re-fetches a still-fresh source, and never registers a new source (that is the add-source command's job, not this one's). Exposed on both surfaces settled in ssm/design/command-surface: a CLI subcommand and an MCP tool.
-> ssm/design/command-surface
-> ssm/design/source-registry
